<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=100018345112192></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100018345112192><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100018345112192>Which skill to specialize in?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100018345112192#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Sep 11th 12:44 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I would like to renew an in-depth discussion on which spell school to specialize in.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have been debating with myself from the first day I bought the game until this day (level 30) and I still have not decided.  <br><br>The two main choices for specialization are: Conjuration, and Evocation.  There are general benefits of each school.<br><br>Conjuration: Used to summon your pets, the Shock of Swords line of Direct-Damage spells, and various other item-summoning spells.  IMHO the item-summoning spells are not important in this decision because they are almost never cast in battle.<br><br>Evocation: Used for various Direct-Damage spells, including the Bolt spells that look like missiles, point blank AoE spells, and the Rain spells (halfway between single target and AoE).<br><br>Up until my current level, I've learned that Direct Damage spells are the spells that I cast the most, and they are also the spells that I cast when I am the most under pressure.  I have not tried, nor learned anything about, chain-casting my pet (I always have one pet that survives over an hour if things go well), so everything that I talk about on this post from now on will involve Direct Damage.<br><br>I am also going to rule out the Rain and Point-blank AoE spells.  I count that I have used Flame Flux only once (from killing sporelings in Runnyeye) and never used a Rain spell in serious situations.  The reason why is simple.  If I am fighting by myself, I will not pull more than one enemy to fight.  If I am fighting with a group, it is much more beneficial to Assist the tanks than to blast all of the enemies at once.  Although there may be uses for these two types of spells, I'm going to rule them out because I don't know enough about them.<br><br>From level 24 all the way until level 33, your best Direct Damage spell was Shock of Spikes.  You will probably cast that spell a lot, and that was probably the reason I accidentally specialized in Conjuration (At the time, I was indecisive).  Until level 34, Conjuration would be the my choice to specialize in.<br><br>At level 34, you get two Evocation-based DD (Direct-Damage) spells: Blaze, and Cinder Bolt.  Blaze is an instant hit (like the Conjuration-based Shock of Swords) and Cinder Bolt is a missile.  Both spells do more damage and are more mana efficient, however, they do take longer to cast.  This makes Shock of Spikes pretty obsolete unless you are fighting fire-based enemies, so Evocation will be the main school that is used for Direct Damage.<br><br>At level 44, you get the Conjuration-based Shock of Swords.  You also get the Evocation-based Elemental Maelstrom, a DoT that does identical magic damage.  Both spells are somewhat similar, and do not make such a big difference in one's playing style that it will require a switch in specialization.<br><br>From level 44 on, the difference between Direct Damage in either school is not as significant, because the percent increase in damage is relatively small compared to lower levels.  This is only a speculation, as I am still a relative newbie.<br><br>In my opinion, Conjuration would be the best skill to specialize in until level 34, when Evocation would be preferable.  After level 44, it becomes ambiguous, and slightly confusing, for me.<br><br>Do you think that I should stick with my Conjuration specialization for good?  Should I re-specialize in the Temple of Solusek Ro when I reach level 34?  If so, should I re-specialize again in Conjuration when I reach level 44?  I have also left out many aspects of the game, including AoE spells (Evocation), and chained pet-casting (Conjuration), which may also be important factors.  Please provide what feedback you can, I would appreciate it very much.  Thank you.<br><br>Rascarcapac, Level 30 Mage, Xev Server.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
